As for where ruins would be, I'll think out loud some more - excuse me if I carry on too long.  Earlier in this discussion you wrote:<br>
<br>
&quot;It's true that if civilisation were to end today there would be no trace of our having existed after tens of thousands of years. A big asteroid would wipe out almost everything in seconds. Even plastic disintegrates in about 10,000 years.&quot;<br>
<br>
It would be interesting to study the decay rates of materials commonly used by advanced civilizations under different conditions.  Materials buried in heavy sediments where things like oxidizing agents can't reach them in large quantaties would decay at different rates than stuff on the surface.  How long could various plastics, stainless steel, (maybe even carbon nanotube based materials?!!) survive under various conditions?  Basic iron, bronze and copper would likely go pretty quickly, but carved granite architecture should survive a very long time.<br>
<br>
If we assume that they mined material like we do, then collapsed mineshafts are probably the best bet for surviving artifacts.  However, all of their mineshafts may have been in the continental shelves, now covered by ocean, since the inland highlands would have been glaciated and difficult to get at.<br>
<br>
It brings us back to the same problem: ruins are likely in formerly coastal areas, which means that they are now underwater, and very likely covered by sediments washed onto the continental shelves by large rivers.  Thus sonar and even satellites are unlikely to pick up very much except seabed; we need to see &quot;through&quot; the upper layers of seabed to see if there is anything lurking on the continental shelves.<br>
<br>
Is there some sort of imaging satellite we could dream up and propose which may be able to &quot;shine&quot; radio waves or something similar through seawater and the upper levels of sea sediment to &quot;map&quot; the deeper layers of terrain?  It would be a nice project to add to the first launch manifest of the Liberty Ship <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I still suspect that anything glaciers could have reached would be ground into nothingness.<br>
<br>
We're also incipiently discussing two scenarios here: we should clarify the possibilities.  The first is that civilization arose during interglacial periods, and that humanity then barely survived glaciations, while the other is that civilization arose during the last glaciation in temperate coastal areas and was then flooded out by deglaciation.<br>
<br>
These two scenarios can easily be combined into a third: civilization arose in the last interglacial period, then got &quot;frozen out&quot;, reestablished itself in coastal areas, then got floode out, then reestablished itself again in our &quot;classical age&quot;.  This cycle may have happened a few times.  All of this would explain why the Egyptians would have mentioned the earth being &quot;remade&quot; a number of times, of which the Greeks are unaware.<br>
<br>
The more I think about this, the more it make sense to me in terms of the Atlantis myth:  Atlantis was supposedly consumed under the oceans, but instead of being a &quot;lost continent&quot; or &quot;lost island&quot;, it was simply civilization(s) on the flooded coastal areas of existing continents.<br>
<br>
If glaciations are ended by an asteroid impact, it would explain the description of fire and brimstone along with massive floods destroying Atlantis: not a volcanic explosion causing a tsunami, but a huge fireball dropping from the sky and sending out not only shockwaves and heatwaves but also torrents of meltwater. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 125<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/16/03 10:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Decay of Artifacts</span><hr size=1> The archeological evidence that has been found shows that<br>
