<br>
If we assume that these people did not surpass the technological level of later Europeans, they didn't want to travel beyond sight of the shore, since they had difficulty with deep-sea navigation.  To go west, they would have gone north and jumped from island to island - ie. the same route as the Vikings took to get to Newfoundland.  According to most paleolithic climate reconstructions, despite the massive ice sheets on the continents, the north Atlantic was still open water around Iceland, Greenland etc., and the lower sea levels would have meant that more underwater hills popped up as islands and the existing islands would have been larger... and the European continental shelf would have extended further northwest.  Newfoundland and Nova Scotia themselves seem to have been under ice sheet, but the Grand Banks to the south and east of Newfoundland could quite likely have been open land, and so under such circumstances &quot;navigation&quot; of the North Atlantic would have been possible.<br>
<br>
There has also been speculation on why one wouldn't see remnants of these civilizations inland - the coastal areas warmed by ocean currents (such as western Europe warmed by the Atlantic current from the Gulf of Mexico area) could have had quite temperate climates, but the temperature would have dropped off rapidly as you went inland.  Modern-day Britain and France would be tundra highlands, the mountains of Scotland were known to have glaciers on them, and the mountains of Wales, Spain etc. were probably also very cold.  Under such geological conditions there may have been more pronounced population clustering in coastal areas, with the interior being left to hunter-gatherers (good old nomadic mammoth hunters etc.).<br>
<br>
This gets us back to the question of &quot;super-civilizations&quot;... well, this thread started off with the fun topics of whether aliens could have visited earth or whether ancient civilizations could have had super-technologies, nuclear power etc.  Now that we've gotten down to the level of brutal realism... these guys were pre-Egyptian, pre-Aztec etc. etc.  Their settlements were probably basically made out of wood buildings and so on.  Myths of such places would have made the cities sound impressive, because in terms of the time, they would have been... but they were probably built of less permanent stuff than things built in the last few thousand years.<br>
<br>
If we check the situation a few thousand years after the end of the ice age and the postulated end of &quot;Atlantis&quot;, we see that things like the henges of Britain and the menhirs of France, which are often cited by the paranormal investigator types as evidence of &quot;super civilization&quot; abilities, may have been stone versions of things which were much more commonly made out of wood:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/434821.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/scien...434821.stm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
If wood was the major construction material in societies then, it probably was earlier on.  Artifacts could have been made of woods like oak (in the short run of up to a few centuries, it can be as good and solid a material as stone).  Under those circumstances only a few stone structures are likely to have been erected, and they would probably have been erected in the largest coastal settlements, not in the smaller settlements inland.  Thus ten thousand years would have sufficed to disorganize older evidence more effectively, with the exception of highly durable pottery and pieces of tools.  Four-thousand year old foundation holes are only just being recognized now; it may be that there are older and more deteriorated ones to be found.<br>
<br>
I believe there's plenty of leeway to find new and older things - we keep finding stuff we didn't expect, like the above example shows.  As I said in my first post, it doesn't quite make sense to me that for most of our existence, anatomically modern humans would have chosen to live only as hunter-gatherers just because some magical worldwide population density number hadn't yet been reached.  Population in the past, as now, would vary according to region.  However, I do admit that this all is a theory - it is entirely feasible that we were all hunter-gatherers until Mesopotamia.<br>
<br>
